In an archive of this newsgroup from last year I came across a thread about
DECsystem-10 timesharing systems on Long Island. The thread referred to LIRICS,
NCODE, and NAG.

Since I was one of the original staff of NCODE, I thought I might share
a little history and also maybe find someone from my past at the same time.

In 1975, the Nassau County Board of Cooperative Educational Services
obtained their own KA-10 (R109 I think) to offer the same sort of
service that LIRICS was offering in Suffolk county.

At the time I was a night-shift computer operator for an IBM 360/30
in the same room as the DEC-10 was being installed into. This was located
in Westbury at the BOCES County Center.

Being bored with loading cards into the 360, I started to mess around
with the DEC-10 which was running overnight disk diagnostics. I really
messed things up and was almost fired for it. But instead they offered me
the job of system programmer to learn from and take over from the DEC resident,
Pat Sweeney.

At the same time, BOCES hired Bob Liquori and he and I became NCODE. We worked
out of two desks in the telephone equipment room and supported users at
many Nassau County High Schools.

After a few years NCODE obtained 2 PDP-11/70s running RSTS/E and these
replaced the -10 for educational computing. The -10 then became abusiness
applications platform (accounting, etc).

NCODE grew and I stayed with it until 1979 when I went to work for DEC in
Colorado Springs as one of the first members of the Telephone Support
Center on the RSTS/E support team.

I could say lots more but I'm not even sure anyone cares.

Brian




